## 10. Interview Questions & Answers

### React & TypeScript Questions

**Q1: Why did you use React with TypeScript instead of plain JavaScript?**

> TypeScript provides compile-time type checking, which caught many bugs during development. For example, when I was implementing the relay control, TypeScript ensured I couldn't accidentally pass a string where a [RelayKey](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/types/sensor.types.ts#32-33) was expected. This saved debugging time and made the code self-documenting.

**Q2: Explain the custom hooks pattern you used.**

> I created specialized hooks like [useSensorData](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/hooks/useSensorData.ts#10-54), [useRelayControl](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/hooks/useRelayControl.ts#11-53), and [useRelayTimers](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/hooks/useRelayTimers.ts#30-190) to separate concerns. Each hook manages its own state and side effects, making the Dashboard component clean and focused on rendering. This also allows reusing the same logic in different components.

**Q3: How do you handle cleanup in your hooks?**

> Every hook that creates subscriptions returns a cleanup function. For example, [useSensorData](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/hooks/useSensorData.ts#10-54) subscribes to Firebase with `onValue` and returns the `off()` function. React's useEffect cleanup mechanism calls this when the component unmounts or dependencies change, preventing memory leaks.

**Q4: Why useCallback for toggle functions?**

> `useCallback` memoizes the function reference, so child components don't re-render unnecessarily. Without it, every parent render creates a new function, causing all children to re-render even if their props haven't changed.

### Firebase Questions

**Q5: Why Firebase Realtime Database instead of Firestore?**

> For IoT data that updates every 2 seconds, Realtime Database is better because:
> - Lower latency (50-100ms vs 100-200ms for Firestore)
> - Better for frequent small updates
> - Simpler for flat data structures like sensor readings
> 
> Firestore is better for complex queries and large documents, which we don't need here.

**Q6: How do you handle the active-low relay logic?**

> Relay modules typically use inverted logic (LOW = ON). I handle this in one place - [relay.service.ts](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/services/firebase/relay.service.ts) - using a configuration constant `RELAY_CONFIG.ACTIVE_LOW`. The service inverts the boolean before writing to Firebase, so components always work with logical ON/OFF.

**Q7: How do real-time updates work?**

> Firebase's `onValue` creates a WebSocket connection. When ESP32 writes to `/sensors/voltage`, Firebase pushes that change to all connected clients. My React hooks receive these updates via callbacks and update state, triggering re-renders.

### IoT & Hardware Questions

**Q8: How does the ESP32 calculate energy consumption?**

> Energy (kWh) = Power (kW) × Time (hours)
> 
> Every 2 seconds, the ESP32:
> 1. Reads voltage and current sensors
> 2. Calculates power (V × I)
> 3. Calculates elapsed time since last reading
> 4. Adds [(power/1000) × (elapsedMs/3600000)](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/App.tsx#15-34) to total energy
> 5. Saves to EEPROM every 60 seconds for persistence

**Q9: Why store energy in EEPROM?**

> EEPROM persists across power cycles. If the ESP32 reboots, it loads the accumulated energy from EEPROM instead of starting from 0. I only save every 60 seconds to reduce EEPROM wear (limited write cycles).

**Q10: How does the timer system work?**

> Timers store [endTime](file:///e:/PROJECTS/clg%20project/IOT%20NEW/src/services/NotificationService.ts#74-83) (absolute Unix timestamp) in Firebase. The client:
> 1. Subscribes to `/timers` in Firebase
> 2. Every second, calculates remaining time: `endTime - now`
> 3. When remaining ≤ 0, executes the action and deletes the timer
> 
> This approach is simple and works without Cloud Functions.

### AI/LLM Questions

**Q11: Why Ollama instead of OpenAI/Gemini?**

> - **Cost**: Free local inference
> - **Privacy**: Data never leaves the local network
> - **Offline**: Works without internet
> - **No rate limits**: Good for development
> 
> Trade-off: Requires local compute and model quality may be lower.

**Q12: How do you prevent the AI from going off-topic?**

> 1. **Keyword filter**: Python proxy checks if the message contains project-related keywords
> 2. **System prompt**: Every request includes instructions to stay on-topic
> 3. **Fallback response**: Non-project questions get "I can only help with Smart Home"

**Q13: Why a Python proxy between React and Ollama?**

> 1. **CORS**: Browsers block cross-origin requests to `localhost:11434`
> 2. **System prompt injection**: Ensures every request has context
> 3. **Request filtering**: Blocks non-project queries server-side
> 4. **Better error messages**: Translates Ollama errors for users

### Architecture Questions

**Q14: How would you add user roles (admin vs regular user)?**

> I would:
> 1. Store role in Firestore: `/users/{uid}/role: "admin" | "user"`
> 2. Add Firebase security rules to restrict writes
> 3. Create a `useUser` hook that fetches the role
> 4. Conditionally render admin features based on role

**Q15: How would you add Google Assistant integration?**

> 1. Create a Firebase Cloud Function that handles Google Actions intents
> 2. Map intents like "turn on light 1" to relay writes
> 3. Link the Actions project to Firebase
> 4. Use OAuth for account linking

**Q16: What would break if 1000 users used this simultaneously?**

> 1. **Firebase costs**: Each user subscribes to real-time updates
> 2. **ESP32 bandwidth**: Would need user isolation
> 3. **Ollama server**: Single instance can't handle concurrent requests
> 
> Solutions: User-specific database paths, load balancing, queue for AI requests.

### Performance Questions

**Q17: How do you handle slow sensors?**

> The ultrasonic sensor uses `pulseIn()` which blocks. I mitigate this by:
> 1. Setting a timeout on `pulseIn`
> 2. Running sensor reads sequentially (not in interrupts)
> 3. Using 2-second intervals so delays are acceptable

**Q18: How do you prevent UI flickering with real-time updates?**

> 1. **Spread merge**: `{ ...prev, ...data }` only updates changed fields
> 2. **React's reconciliation**: Only DOM nodes that change are updated
> 3. **Memoization**: Child components use `React.memo` to skip renders

